[normal]              
[normal]Of the ten responses received, nine indicated that Scrutiny had received evidence relevant to the terms of reference for this Health Select Committee Inquiry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.0 [bold]              [bold]Financial Pressures[bold]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]Nine out of ten of the responses showed that Scrutiny had received evidence regarding financial pressure in the health and social care system. Examples that were given included:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hospital Emergency care
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sustainability of acute hospital services
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Closure of mental health services
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Increased charges and fees for Adult Care Services
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Reduction in Continuing Healthcare putting pressure on local authority adult care budgets
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Cost pressures resulting in reduction in early intervention services
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Pooling resources between organisations to reduce cost pressures
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.0 [bold]              [bold]Long Term Viability of NHS and FT Trusts[bold]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]The issue that provided the second largest number of responses related to the work of Scrutiny on the long term viability of NHS and FT Trusts. Seven Authorities provided evidence in response to this question. The West Midlands is a particularly interesting area to consider as there are two acute trusts that have been recognised as unsustainable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Mid Staffordshire FT Trust which has been reviewed by the Trust Special Administrators
[normal] and the George Eliot NHS Trust that has announced that it will go out to tender for a partner. In both these areas Scrutiny has a key role. The evidence below provides information on the work by Scrutiny on these authorities and other areas:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]Rugby Borough Council Scrutiny
[normal]Discussions with the UHCW NHS Trust regarding their Integrated Business Plan and their plans for the future of St Cross Hospital in Rugby, which has seen a significant reduction in the services it offers over a number of years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Councillors have been reassured that the hospital is not under threat and remains an integral part of the business of the Trust.
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]Staffordshire County Council Scrutiny
[normal]Trust Special Administrators recommendations in relation to Mid Staffordshire NHS FT
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]clinical and financial stability and the population covered by the Trust.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]Telford and Wrekin Borough Council Scrutiny
[normal]The Joint Health Overview and Scrutiny Committee with Shropshire had received reports regarding concerns at both hospital sites at Shrewsbury and Telford which had resulted in a Risk Summit being convened by the NHS England Area Team. While the Chairs of the Joint HOSC were informed that the immediate quality issues were being addressed, the Committee still had concerns about the long term viability of the services across the two hospital sites. The Joint HOSC Chairs recognised that the issues faced by the acute Trust were symptoms of the issues within the whole local health and social care system. Following discussions with all key stakeholders within the NHS and Local Authorities, including the Health and Wellbeing Board Chairs and the Local Area Team, the Joint HOSC held a meeting and asked the local NHS commissioners, providers and NHS England Area Team to set out what are the key issues for the local health economy and how the different organisations would work together to resolve these. The Joint HOSC was pleased with the joined up response from the local NHS and will continue to monitor the CCGs’ Commissioning Plans that will follow from the Call to Action consultation and the 
[normal]development of the Excellent and Sustainable Clinical Services Strategy which will consider the future provision of acute and community hospital services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]              
[normal]Warwickshire County Council Scrutiny
[normal]The Adult Social Care and Health OSC in Warwickshire scrutinises the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]George Eliot Hospital NHS Trust.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]              
[normal]In 2011 GEH was not considered sustainable in the long-term and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]was not able to apply for Foundation Trust Status without a strategic partner.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The GEH Board produced a strategic outline case setting the context and providing an overview of the hospital – its size, patient profile, the people it serves and wider partner agencies and reported on early work that had been undertaken to further define and assess options for the best model / approach to a strategic partnership that would provide the sustainability required to both apply for FT status and build on into the future.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7
[normal]              
[normal]This work was interrupted
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]by the Robert Francis Inquiry into Mid Staffs and the subsequent recommendations to come from that Inquiry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This led to the Keogh Review and the GEH was identified as one of the 14 Keogh Review Hospitals due to the high mortality rates at the hospital.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8
[normal]              
[normal]GEH has been placed in ‘special measures’ while plans to improve the quality of care were taken forward.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.9
[normal]              
[normal]GEH has published its Improvement Plan and the actions to address the Keogh recommendations have been agreed by the Trust Board.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.10
[normal]              
[normal]GEH has been partnered with University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust with a view to supporting the work it is doing to deliver the Keogh Review recommendations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.11
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]GEH had also received the go-ahead from government to go out to tender for a partner, and for the first time ever, it is a tender for the whole hospital rather than for a service within the hospital and it is open to public and private organisations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.12
[normal]              
[normal]All of the above issues are being monitored by the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Adult Social Care and Health OSC on an on going basis, as well as more defined quality performance scrutiny
[normal] 
[normal]around areas such as mortality, pressure ulcers etc (as identified by the Quality Accounts Task and Finish Group).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.13
[normal]              
[normal]The long-term sustainability issues being faced by GEH are not unique to this hospital, and will possibly face most small general hospitals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.0 [bold]              [bold]NHS Efficiencies and Cuts[bold]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]Evidence provided by Local Government Scrutiny across the West Midlands regarding the efficiencies or cuts made by the NHS illustrated the depth of the work undertaken by Scrutiny Committees and the complexity of the organisations and services involved. The responses showed that the evidence received by Scrutiny related to both service and organisational reconfiguration. Some service reconfigurations were clinically driven e.g. the review of stroke services identified by scrutiny in Telford and Wrekin, while scrutiny in Solihull identified the oversight role of the Scrutiny Committee in the Heart of England FT 
[normal]Transformation Programme. Scrutiny at Rugby Borough Council had received detailed evidence regarding the development of the University Hospitals Coventry and Warwickshire NHS Trust’s Integrated Business Plan which included information about QIPP savings.
[normal]5.2 
[normal]              
[normal]Telford &amp; Wrekin Council Scrutiny
[normal]The Health and Adult Care Scrutiny Committee carried out a detailed review of Continuing Health Care (CHC). The Committee received evidence from the Local Authority  that there has been a 73% cut in the PCT spend on CHC from £13.9 million in 2009/10 to £3.8 million in 2011/12. The total reduction in CHC over this period of £10.1million has resulted in an additional burden on the Council’s Adult Care budget of £8.5 million, with the balance falling on people who self fund.The PCT / CCG has made one off contributions to the Local Authority to offset an element of these costs. The Scrutiny Committee has made recommendations to the CCG and Health and Wellbeing Board which address the underlying issues regarding the level of CHC funding. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.0[bold]              [bold]Integration of Health and Social Care[bold]6.1
[normal]              
[normal]Several responses provided examples of the evidence considered by Local Government Scrutiny on the integration of health and social care services. The examples provided were:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Staffordshire Adult Social Services integrated into the Stoke-on-Trent
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Partnership NHS Trust which was formed as a result of the amalgamation of NHS North Staffordshire , NHS North Staffordshire, NHS Stoke-on –Trent and South Staffordshire PCT
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The amalgamation and integration of the services was
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]brought to Staffordshire County Council Assets and Budget Scrutiny Committee Integration of health and social care came about as a result of the creation of the Staffordshire and Stoke on Trent Partnership Trust.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Scrutiny in Solihull MBC : The HCSB have received a number of reports on the way health and social care are working together through an ‘Accountable Care Partnership’ and will be monitoring the work, outcomes and efficiencies being progressed through a new integrated care project which has just been set up. (This work is being sponsored by the Health and Wellbeing Board)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.0 [bold]              [bold]Impact on Adult Social Care Services Following the 2010 Spending Review[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1
[normal]              
[normal]Scrutiny in five local authorities responded that Committees had received evidence on the impact on the provision of adult social care following the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary savings. Examples of the issues considered by the Committees are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fairer charging and eligibility criteria
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Financial pressure on Adult services which may result in the local authority raising the threshold for local authority funded care to critical
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The funding for Adult Social Care must be seen in the context of the overall reduction in funding for local government and that efficiency savings in the NHS can result in additional costs for the local authority
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Implication of the Care and Support Bill
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Evidence in performance and Local Account reports
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2
[normal]              
[normal]Telford and Wrekin Council Scrutiny
[normal]The Budget and Finance Scrutiny Committee in Telford and Wrekin has monitored the financial pressures on the Adult Care budget following the 2010 Spending Review. In addition to this, as part of the Health and Adult Care Scrutiny Committee’s review of Continuing Health Care members received evidence that the average reduction in funding for Local Government was initially 27%, but following later announcements this increased to 33%.   A detailed report will be considered by the Health and Adult Care Scrutiny Committee and members of the Budget and Finance Scrutiny Committee on the 4
[normal]th
[normal] November 2013.This sets out the pressures on the Council’s Adult Care budget which accounts for 36% of the Council’s spend and over 80% of this is spent directly on providing care. The Adult Social Care budget has been reduced by £7million which has been achieved through efficiencies, new ways of working and staff reductions.  The Adult Care budget is expected to find a further £6.5 million to achieve the savings required by 2015/16 while there continues to be an underlying growth in the number of people needing services compared with the number of people leaving the service. The Scrutiny Committee will consider the financial improvement plan put in place to manage the Adult Care Services budget.
